</p>
</div>
<div data-type="solution" id="fs-idm14944944">
<p id="fs-idm41104416">(a)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span></p><span data-type="media" id="fs-idm63850832" data-alt="A Lewis structure shows two oxygen atoms double bonded together, and each has two lone pairs of electrons.">
<img src="/resources/00f59fc8b8ff94f5c3efbf1c263727610006249c/CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7a_img.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="A Lewis structure shows two oxygen atoms double bonded together, and each has two lone pairs of electrons."/>
</span><p><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
In this case, the Lewis structure is inadequate to depict the fact that experimental studies have shown two unpaired electrons in each oxygen molecule.<span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
(b)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span></p><span data-type="media" id="fs-idm76406432" data-alt="A Lewis structure shows a carbon atom that is single bonded to two hydrogen atoms and double bonded to an oxygen atom. The oxygen atom has two lone pairs of electrons.">
<img src="/resources/c8f4ad9f81a905b10c1b466dc64b2ac3a51bca6e/CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7b_img.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="A Lewis structure shows a carbon atom that is single bonded to two hydrogen atoms and double bonded to an oxygen atom. The oxygen atom has two lone pairs of electrons."/>
</span><p><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
(c)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span></p><span data-type="media" id="fs-idp37290624" data-alt="A Lewis structure shows an arsenic atom single bonded to three fluorine atoms. Each fluorine atom has a lone pair of electrons.">
<img src="/resources/acda149c4a3c4a3624fc63b5fc39e8ebf7e7ce7e/CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7c_img.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="A Lewis structure shows an arsenic atom single bonded to three fluorine atoms. Each fluorine atom has a lone pair of electrons."/>
</span><p><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
(d)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span></p><span data-type="media" id="fs-idm29017600" data-alt="A Lewis structure shows a nitrogen atom with a lone pair of electrons single bonded to a chlorine atom that has three lone pairs of electrons. The nitrogen is also double bonded to an oxygen which has two lone pairs of electrons.">
<img src="/resources/ee84bfcaf2ab930888664250b864860c9b76ad08/CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7d_img.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="A Lewis structure shows a nitrogen atom with a lone pair of electrons single bonded to a chlorine atom that has three lone pairs of electrons. The nitrogen is also double bonded to an oxygen which has two lone pairs of electrons."/>
</span><p><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
(e)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span></p><span data-type="media" id="fs-idm67346912" data-alt="A Lewis structure shows a silicon atom that is single bonded to four chlorine atoms. Each chlorine atom has three lone pairs of electrons.">
<img src="/resources/27b4776cd7f5aa9079e61a4032a835b354755783/CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7e_img.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="A Lewis structure shows a silicon atom that is single bonded to four chlorine atoms. Each chlorine atom has three lone pairs of electrons."/>
</span><p><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
(f)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span></p><span data-type="media" id="fs-idm62683280" data-alt="A Lewis structure shows an oxygen atom with a lone pair of electrons single bonded to three hydrogen atoms. The structure is surrounded by brackets with a superscripted positive sign.">
<img src="/resources/5d00631164f84c50ce8345bcb0642c4d57b5ce9c/CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7f_img.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="A Lewis structure shows an oxygen atom with a lone pair of electrons single bonded to three hydrogen atoms. The structure is surrounded by brackets with a superscripted positive sign."/>
</span><p><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
(g)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span></p><span data-type="media" id="fs-idm804688" data-alt="A Lewis structure shows a nitrogen atom single bonded to four hydrogen atoms. The structure is surrounded by brackets with a superscripted positive sign.">
<img src="/resources/1496a260766566422d4fc041e4378de8823270b5/CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7g_img.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="A Lewis structure shows a nitrogen atom single bonded to four hydrogen atoms. The structure is surrounded by brackets with a superscripted positive sign."/>
</span><p><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
(h)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span></p><span data-type="media" id="fs-idp792848" data-alt="A Lewis structure shows a boron atom single bonded to four fluorine atoms. Each fluorine atom has three lone pairs of electrons. The structure is surrounded by brackets with a superscripted negative sign.">
<img src="/resources/bc43b891fe370b3af381a0b8067e9b728b8476a6/CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7h_img.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="A Lewis structure shows a boron atom single bonded to four fluorine atoms. Each fluorine atom has three lone pairs of electrons. The structure is surrounded by brackets with a superscripted negative sign."/>
</span><p><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
(i)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span></p><span data-type="media" id="fs-idp7083808" data-alt="A Lewis structure shows two carbon atoms that are triple bonded together. Each carbon is also single bonded to a hydrogen atom.">
<img src="/resources/32093b55d7a751f82d44688a1f010af204623b6c/CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7i_img.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="A Lewis structure shows two carbon atoms that are triple bonded together. Each carbon is also single bonded to a hydrogen atom."/>
</span><p><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
(j)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span></p><span data-type="media" id="fs-idm28530944" data-alt="A Lewis structure shows a carbon atom that is triple bonded to a nitrogen atom that has one lone pair of electrons. The carbon is also single bonded to a chlorine atom that has three lone pairs of electrons.">
<img src="/resources/de3c4e8f30a19930d21696550c2fb07a0af1b5aa/CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7j_img.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="A Lewis structure shows a carbon atom that is triple bonded to a nitrogen atom that has one lone pair of electrons. The carbon is also single bonded to a chlorine atom that has three lone pairs of electrons."/>
</span><p><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
(k)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span></p><span data-type="media" id="fs-idm148703504" data-alt="A Lewis structure shows two carbon atoms joined with a triple bond. A superscripted 2 positive sign lies to the right of the second carbon.">
<img src="/resources/c5470a7fe54da6d29e36ff451bacb05784358c48/CNX_Chem_07_03_Question7k_img.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="A Lewis structure shows two carbon atoms joined with a triple bond. A superscripted 2 positive sign lies to the right of the second carbon."/>
</span></div>
